<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is baker's percentage in sourdough?", answer: "Baker's percentage expresses each ingredient as a percentage of the total flour weight. Flour is always 100%. If you have 500g flour and 350g water, the hydration is 70%. This system makes it easy to scale recipes to any size." },
  { question: "What hydration level should I use for sourdough?", answer: "Beginners should start at 65-70% hydration for a manageable dough. Experienced bakers often work at 75-85% for a more open crumb. Above 85% produces ciabatta-like bread with very large holes. Lower hydration (60-65%) is good for sandwich loaves." },
  { question: "How much starter should I use?", answer: "A typical sourdough recipe uses 15-25% starter relative to total flour. Using less starter (10-15%) extends fermentation time and develops more complex flavors. Using more starter (25-30%) speeds up fermentation." },
  { question: "Does starter hydration matter?", answer: "Yes. A 100% hydration starter (equal parts flour and water by weight) is most common. If your starter is at a different hydration, the calculator accounts for the flour and water contributed by the starter so your overall dough hydration remains accurate." },
  { question: "How much salt should I add to sourdough?", answer: "The standard amount is 2% of total flour weight. This is about 10g of salt per 500g of flour. Some bakers prefer 1.8-2.2%. Salt strengthens gluten, controls fermentation rate, and enhances flavor." }
]) %>

